snippet.textDisplay: Smh at some of these people in the comments. The actual general election in November is basically the only way we elect a president. You can write any person’s name in the world on that ballot. Gritty (the Philadelphia Flyers’ mascot) actually received votes in 2016. The primaries are just the individual party’s way of nominating one candidate that all of the party’s members can rally behind as one party. Ideally there wouldn’t just be two dominant parties, but the third parties never gain enough support. People think the government literally set it up this way, when in reality, it’s the parties that set it up this way so that the entire political party could all put their support behind one candidate for the general election.
snippet.textOriginal: Smh at some of these people in the comments. The actual general election in November is basically the only way we elect a president. Bernie has the best outreach, both due to personal investment, and because his supporters are by far the most enthusiastic and all come together to canvas for him in every state.

He will do especially well in states with high minority populations. Biden may have name recognition from the first black president choice of vice, but that advantage is diminishing significantly. After all, Biden is the crusty old white conservative Obama chose to get white moderates to vote for him -- he's even kinda racist himself. Bernie is a very close second in the African American vote, and dominates the Hispanic vote. Impoverished workers will vote for him, unions all over endorse him (after all, one of his main policies is cutting the legal chains that restrict union collective action). He is the second choice of Biden and Warren supporters.

snippet.textDisplay:
We should be voting on the same day. I'm getting sick of arguing over who goes first. It wouldn't be an issue if everyone voted at the same time. Use ranked choice voting so that it could still be narrowed down. I get that its supposedly for less well known candidates, however many states aren't even representative and that can change as people change.

I live in WA idk why we even vote at all. Our primary is so late it doesn't matter. I dont think yang would have won but if a different state went first he may have performed better say on the west coast. Which could have changed at least the early dropouts.

Picking a state to go first stacks it too. Especially when that state is white and conservative. It is a barrier to progress. If voters want to stop giving an advantage based on name recognition, they should stop voting based on name recognition and take a minute to read something.
